      <hedline>
        <hl1>J. Edgar Hoover And Birmingham</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Lewis Friedman letter says latest evidence of J Edgar Hoover's immoral rule over FBI in his decades as director is note, in May 18 article on arrests in 1963 black church bombing, that Hoover had shelved investigation in 1960's despite optimism of his subordinates in Birmingham that it could be successsfully prosecuted</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''2 Charged in 1963 Church Blast That Killed 4 Birmingham Girls'' (front page, May 18), you note that ''J. Edgar Hoover, the former F.B.I. director, had shelved the investigation in the 1960's despite the optimism of his subordinates in Birmingham that it could be successfully prosecuted.''</p>
        <p>This is another example of Mr. Hoover's immoral rule over the F.B.I. in his decades as director.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''2 Charged in 1963 Church Blast That Killed 4 Birmingham Girls'' (front page, May 18), you note that ''J. Edgar Hoover, the former F.B.I. director, had shelved the investigation in the 1960's despite the optimism of his subordinates in Birmingham that it could be successfully prosecuted.''</p>
        <p>This is another example of Mr. Hoover's immoral rule over the F.B.I. in his decades as director.</p>
        <p>Added to his vicious attacks on the Rev. Dr. Martin Luther King Jr., his gathering of intelligence on other Americans gave him enormous power under both Democratic and Republican administrations.</p>
        <p>F.B.I. headquarters in Washington was named in homage to Hoover. It is time that our government rename it.</p>
        <p>For our government to honor a man who, in retrospect, has so dishonored government, law enforcement and our country is wrong.</p>
        <p>LEWIS  FRIEDMAN  Brooklyn, May 18, 2000</p>
      </block>
